<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Gamma Correction" class="currentChild" href="Gamma_Correction">Gamma Correction</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A modification of the <a title="Contrast" href="Contrast">contrast</a> of a photographic image by means of adjusting the <a title="Tone Curve" href="Tone_Curve">tone curve</a>s for the image. Essentially, gamma correction involves increasing or decreasing the <a title="Middle Tone" href="Middle_Tone">middle tone</a> value, depending upon the desired correction. For example, a reproduction of a red fire hydrant may reproduce too dark. By reducing the middle tone, the dark color—<a title="Cyan" href="Cyan">cyan</a>—will be reduced, allowing the lighter color—<a title="Magenta" href="Magenta">magenta</a>—to peek through to a greater extent and make the image brighter. Gamma correction—also called <a title="Tone Correction" href="Tone_Correction">tone correction</a>—is often incorrectly confused with <a title="Color Correction" href="Color_Correction">color correction</a>. (See also <a title="Contrast" href="Contrast">Contrast</a>.) 
</p>
